Hi Carles,

Le 09/06/2015 13:55, Carles Gomez Montenegro a écrit :
> Hi Alex,
>
> Do you have any news on any Bluetooth SIG plans to create some
> version of BLE that can be compatible with classic Bluetooth?

Unfortunately no, I have no such news.

Is there a link person here in 6lo to whom we can ask about the
future plans of BTLE at Bluetooth SIG?

> Since the Bluetooth protocol stack has been significantly redesigned
> for Bluetooth Low Energy, these are actually two different
> technologies, similar to considering IEEE 802.15.4 and IEEE 802.11.
> We don't expect them to interoperate.

Well one wouldnt expect an IP/15.4 device to talk to an IP/11 device yet
IP/15.4 is precisely the same stack as IP/11 - there are no mandatory
differences between RFC2464 and RFC4944.

What we have here is a direction in which the IP/BTLE stack becomes
different than an IP/Bluetooth stack.  The difference lies in the Header
Compression mandate.  Were it optional we'd talk compatibility.

(I am saying this after having just run pand on Bluetooth on linux,
captured packets with wireshark, and checked whether or not there's
header compression; could you please wireshark on BTLE and tell me
whether there is Header Compression?  thanks.).

Alex

>
> Best regards,
>
> Carles
