> different than an IP/Bluetooth stack.  The difference lies in the Header
> Compression mandate.  Were it optional we'd talk compatibility.

No: the difference is significantly greater. The solutions for IP over
Bluetooth I am aware of differ significantly in the layer(s) between IP
and L2CAP from what there is between IPv6 and L2CAP in the IPv6 over BLE
draft.

The purpose of the IPv6 over BLE draft is to allow IPv6 run over BLE.
Enabling what you suggest would be a completely different story.

And I think we should not design for something that just does not exist
and seems highly unlikely to exist in the future.

> (I am saying this after having just run pand on Bluetooth on linux,
> captured packets with wireshark, and checked whether or not there's
> header compression; could you please wireshark on BTLE and tell me
> whether there is Header Compression?  thanks.).

Well, if IPv6 over BLE has been implemented per draft-ietf-6lo-btle, then
header compression should be there.

Best regards,

Carles


