Hi Alex,

< snip >

>>>From the IPv6 over BLE draft, section 2, 1st paragraph:
>>
>>     "Bluetooth Special Interest Group (Bluetooth SIG) has introduced two
>>     trademarks, Bluetooth Smart for single-mode devices (a device that
>>     only supports Bluetooth LE) and Bluetooth Smart Ready for dual-mode
>>     devices (devices that support both Bluetooth and Bluetooth LE).  In
>>     the rest of the document, the term Bluetooth LE refers to both types
>>     of devices."
>
> That paragraph of the document is confusing for a couple of reasons.
>
> Is the term Bluetooth LE referring to both single-mode devices and
> dual-mode devices?  Or is it referring to both Bluetooth and to
> Bluetooth LE devices?

- A 'Bluetooth Smart' device only supports Bluetooth LE (as stated in the
paragraph).

- A 'Bluetooth Smart Ready' device has typically two different radio
interfaces (and two different upper layer protocol stacks): one of them
supports Bluetooth LE, whereas the other one supports classic Bluetooth.

> The second reason of confusion is that it may try to specify
> IPv6/Bluetooth behaviour which is wrong.  IPv6/Bluetooth does not use HC.

The paragraph comes after it has been clearly stated in section 1 that:

"This document specifies the details of IPv6 transmission over Bluetooth
LE links."

Nevertheless, I agree that it may not be so clear to a reader without
Bluetooth expertise that 'Bluetooth' and 'Bluetooth LE' refer to
different, non-interoperable technologies. Please see a proposal below.

> Maybe that paragraph above should be clarified.

Would the following be clearer?

NEW:
       "Bluetooth Special Interest Group (Bluetooth SIG) has introduced two
       trademarks, Bluetooth Smart for single-mode devices (a device that
       only supports Bluetooth LE) and Bluetooth Smart Ready for dual-mode
       devices (devices that support both Bluetooth and Bluetooth LE; note
       that Bluetooth and Bluetooth LE are different, non-interoperable
       radio technologies). In the rest of the document, the term Bluetooth
       LE refers to both types of devices."

< snip >

Regards,

Carles


