Hi Carsten,

Thanks for reading the draft.

Let me think about your life cycle question - if we need to add something,
that=B9s fine. We can do that.


As for DHCP vs. 6775, my company, as well as others, have proposed a
network that relies on RPL DIO messages to establish neighbor and routing
connectivity to the network. This type of network has no IPv6 ND traffic
on the network (yet).

Rather than overload neighbor discovery with more and more configuration
duty, we=B9re using something that is designed for network configuration.
We could have used RFC 6775 =B3only=B2 to disseminate compression contexts,
but we also have to configure other parameters, such as:

https://tools.ietf.org/html/draft-ietf-roll-mpl-parameter-configuration-04


So we=B9ve already bitten the bullet on using DHCPv6, which will come in
handy if/when we need to configure other parameters that NAN devices may
need to know - it seemed a better long term solution than burdening RPL
DIOs or ND messages with even more configuration options.

We=B9re also using the =B3Rapid Commit=B2 option to limit the DHCP traffic =
on
our constrained network, along with an idea or two from Jonathan Hui=B9s
original draft on DHCP for 6LoWPANs
(https://tools.ietf.org/html/draft-hui-6lowpan-dhcp-00)

Thanks again for your comments

Randy



On 6/9/15, 3:42 PM, "Carsten Bormann" <cabo@tzi.org> wrote:

>Hi Randy,
>
>Turner, Randy wrote:
>> DHCP configuration of RFC 6282 compression contexts
>
>RFC 6282 compression contexts need to be identical between each pair of
>compressing and decompressing nodes, i.e., throughout the LoWPAN.  RFC
>6775 provides a way to disseminate this information that is relatively
>robust in this respect; there is also a discussion about the life cycle
>considerations that apply here in Section 7.2 of RFC 6775.
>A quick scan of the new draft does not yield answers to the obvious
>questions:
>-- how is the consistency throughout the LoWPAN ensured?
>-- how are life cycles managed?
>
>Actually, I would like to have additional information about why you
>think that DHCP is a better way to manage compression context
>information than the mechanisms provided in RFC 6775.
>
>Gr=FC=DFe, Carsten


