Hi Carles,

Le 09/06/2015 19:17, Carles Gomez Montenegro a écrit :
> Hi Alex,
>
> < snip >
>
>>>> From the IPv6 over BLE draft, section 2, 1st paragraph:
>>>
>>> "Bluetooth Special Interest Group (Bluetooth SIG) has introduced
>>>  two trademarks, Bluetooth Smart for single-mode devices (a
>>> device that only supports Bluetooth LE) and Bluetooth Smart Ready
>>> for dual-mode devices (devices that support both Bluetooth and
>>> Bluetooth LE).  In the rest of the document, the term Bluetooth
>>> LE refers to both types of devices."
>>
>> That paragraph of the document is confusing for a couple of
>> reasons.
>>
>> Is the term Bluetooth LE referring to both single-mode devices and
>>  dual-mode devices?  Or is it referring to both Bluetooth and to
>> Bluetooth LE devices?
>
> - A 'Bluetooth Smart' device only supports Bluetooth LE (as stated in
> the paragraph).

Ok, a Bluetooth Smart device supports only Bluetooth LE, and Bluetooth
Smart Ready device support both BTLE and classic BT.  (I hope the
Bluetooth SIG agrees with it, because the spec Bluetooth 4.0 seems to
include BTLE).

> - A 'Bluetooth Smart Ready' device has typically two different radio
>  interfaces

I agree it's two different technologies, but I doubt a Bluetooth Smart
Ready device has two different radio interfaces.

My recent laptop has only one Intel Wireless Bluetooth 4.0 radio
interface in the hardware list of Windows ("4.0 " means the spec that
includes text of "Low Energy"). That single interface connects to my old
logitech bluetooth 2.0 keyboard _and_ to my new fitbit flex bluetooth 4.0.

> (and two different upper layer protocol stacks): one of them supports
> Bluetooth LE, whereas the other one supports classic Bluetooth.

Ok, I assume a moment we have a computer with two interfaces: one BTLE
only, and one classic-BT.  What does look like a packet dump of IPv6 on
the BTLE only interface?  Does it include HC?

(I do have here a BTLE-only device, and with packet dumps,
  but that does not have IP).

>> The second reason of confusion is that it may try to specify
>> IPv6/Bluetooth behaviour which is wrong.  IPv6/Bluetooth does not
>> use HC.
>
> The paragraph comes after it has been clearly stated in section 1
> that:
>
> "This document specifies the details of IPv6 transmission over
> Bluetooth LE links."
>
> Nevertheless, I agree that it may not be so clear to a reader
> without Bluetooth expertise that 'Bluetooth' and 'Bluetooth LE' refer
> to different, non-interoperable technologies. Please see a proposal
> below.
>
>> Maybe that paragraph above should be clarified.
>
> Would the following be clearer?
>
> NEW: "Bluetooth Special Interest Group (Bluetooth SIG) has introduced
> two trademarks, Bluetooth Smart for single-mode devices (a device
> that only supports Bluetooth LE) and Bluetooth Smart Ready for
> dual-mode devices (devices that support both Bluetooth and Bluetooth
> LE; note that Bluetooth and Bluetooth LE are different,
> non-interoperable radio technologies). In the rest of the document,
> the term Bluetooth LE refers to both types of devices."

Thanks for a new formulation.

It clarifies that BT and BTLE are different and incompatible, it is
good.  But "devices" appears too many times and refers to different things.

And, it means that whenever the RFC says
"IPv6 REQUIRES HC over Bluetooth LE" we mean
"IPv6 REQUIRES HC over classical Bluetooth" as well.

I doubt it is the intended meaning?

Because IPv6 does not use HC over classical Bluetooth.  We dont want to 
introduce HC to devices that support only IPv6/BT and not IPv6/BTLE, 
right?  Because that would be introducing incompatibility with old 
Bluetooth devices which dont support HC.

I suggest the following text:
> Bluetooth Special Interest Group (Bluetooth SIG) has introduced two
> trademarks and logos: Bluetooth Smart for single-mode devices (a
> device that only supports Bluetooth LE) and Bluetooth Smart Ready for
> dual-mode devices (a device that supports both Bluetooth and
> Bluetooth LE; note that Bluetooth and Bluetooth LE are different,
> non-interoperable radio technologies).  In the rest of this document,
> the term Bluetooth LE refers to devices that support only Bluetooth
> LE."

Can this text lead to clarification?

Alex

>
> < snip >
>
> Regards,
>
> Carles
>
>
