No.

Focusing on the last sentence: the document describes how IPv6 runs over
Bluetooth LE interfaces. There may be devices that only support Bluetooth
LE, and devices that support both Bluetooth LE and additional 
non-Bluetooth LE interfaces.

Please find below a new proposal (see the changes in the last sentence).

NEW:
      Bluetooth Special Interest Group (Bluetooth SIG) has introduced
      two trademarks, Bluetooth Smart for single-mode devices (a device
      that only supports Bluetooth LE) and Bluetooth Smart Ready for
      dual-mode devices (devices that support both Bluetooth and Bluetooth
      LE; note that Bluetooth and Bluetooth LE are different,
      non-interoperable radio technologies). In the rest of the document,
      the term Bluetooth LE is used regardless of whether this technology
      is supported by a single-mode or dual-mode device.

(And please recall that the document states in section 1 that "This
document specifies the details of IPv6 transmission over Bluetooth LE
links". So any other technology such as 'classic Bluetooth' or others is
out of the scope of this document.)

Best regards,

Carles


