Le 11/06/2015 12:56, Carles Gomez Montenegro a écrit :
> Hi Alex,
>
>> Le 11/06/2015 11:17, Carles Gomez Montenegro a écrit :
>>> Hi Alex,
>>>
>>>> Le 09/06/2015 13:55, Carles Gomez Montenegro a écrit :
>>>>> Hi Alex,
>>>>>
>>>>> Do you have any news on any Bluetooth SIG plans to create some
>>>>> version of BLE that can be compatible with classic Bluetooth?
>>>>
>>>> Here is some news: Bluetooth 4.2 seems to be offering a procedure
>>>> to negotiate larger data packets ("LE Data Packet Length
>>>> Extension") (instead of currently 27 bytes).  If that materializes
>>>> can it be assumed that Header Compression for IPv6 be less
>>>> necessary when running IPv6/BTLE?
>>>>
>>>> Alex
>>>
>>> Just to avoid possible confusion: those 'news' are not related with
>>> my original question above. That is, Bluetooth 4.2 is *not* a move
>>> to making Bluetooth LE "backwards compatible" with classic
>>> Bluetooth.
>>
>> Ok.
>>
>> But  those old news are still a potential way towards making IPv6 work
>> over BTLE just as it works over Bluetooth.
>
> No: it is just a way to extend the size of Bluetooth LE data channel PDUs,
> with the purpose of achieving greater throughput in applications that may
> need so and/or in any case decreasing the relative penalty of packet
> overhead.

There we may need IP then.

> By the way, the Bluetooth 4.2 Link Layer packet format supports only up to
> 257-octet upper layer PDUs, so this is anyway not fulfilling the 1280-byte
> MTU IPv6 requirement.

This should be told to Bluetooth SIG.  Bluetooth SIG should take it as a 
requirement.  They can devise several ways of satisfying it with very 
good compromises.

IP does not necessarily need to be stripped off of its headers in order 
to satisfy that requirement.

Other SDOs did that in the past and it worked fine.

>>> Regarding your question, you always have energy and throughput gains
>>> by using header compression.
>>
>> I doubt it is significant enough worth the effort.  Eliminating 38bytes
>> from a stream of hundreds of bytes can not save too much energy.
>
> IMO, 38 bytes vs 257 bytes is significant. And note that packets are not
> 'mandatorily large' in Bluetooth 4.2. There will still be many short IPv6
> packets over Bluetooth 4.2.

This is wrong.

One must have 1280byte sized packets in order to have IP.

There are no shorter IPv6 packets.

One may think about a hypothetical 41byte packet (base header and 1byte 
data), but that is just hypothetical.

>> If you want to save energy then the most energy saving is by _not_ using
>> IP.  That is much more gain in terms of energy.
>
> Two points here:
>
> 1) We want to connect devices to the Internet (thus we want IP to run on
> these devices).

So you must conenct it in a manner that satisfies the current 
architecture of the Internet.

If you connect in a different manner then that is not a connection to 
the Internet.

> 2) Are you arguing that the 6LoWPAN, 6Lo, 6TiSCH, CoRE, etc. work is
> leading to bad design which is not energy efficient?

I dont understand why you conclude that way?   Are these groups 
targetting energy-efficiency?  Each seems to have different goal than 
energy efficiency (i.e. 6tisch looks at time slots, core looks at a 
disconnected webservice, etc.).

>> If you want to save energy at IP layer then you must consider
>> heterogeneous links, i.e. beyond BTLE.  If you consider heterogeneous
>> links then you must consider inter-operability with existing ways of IP
>> working on these links.  And these dont use Header Compression.
>
> In draft-ietf-6lo-btle we are only concerned about running IPv6 over
> Bluetooth LE.

Ok.  I argue that IPv6/BTLE makes no sense if the Internet connection is 
not considered.

IPv6/BTLE will consume much more energy than no-IPv6.

> And, do you intend to say that routers with e.g. a 6LoWPAN (over 15.4)
> interface and other interfaces such as Ethernet or Wifi don't work?

No, I am not saying that, I dont udnerstand why you imply I would say so?

A router with a 6lowpan/15.4 does not necessarily _require_ HEader 
Compression - it is optional.   As a matter of fact 6lowpan/15.4 is 
optional altogether - you can have IPv6/15.4 without 6lowpan, it works.

>>> If the involved packets are 'large', the benefits are lower in
>>> relative terms than with 'short' packets, but there are still
>>> benefits.
>>
>> I think the benefits exist, maybe like 1-8 percent.  I think they are
>> not worth the risk of losing interoperability.
>
> No: greater percent. Please see above.
>
>> I think interoperability should come first - i.e. the capability of
>> getting a message through, in an end-to-end manner.  Then energy saving
>> should come.
>
> The goal of draft-ietf-6lo-btle is to allow interoperability between
> devices that run IPv6 over Bluetooth LE.

That is a good goal.  But it is only half of the story.  If you only 
need this half, then IP is not needed - it is a hurdle.

The document should  also have the goal to communicate packets from a 
BTLE-only device across the Internet, all the way to another BTLE-only 
device.  I should be able to ping6 a BTLE device across the Internet 
right now.

That is the Internet.

Otherwise you talk small islands of little things disconnected from each 
other and from the Internet.

>> Of course, energy savings are important.  But we need to think
>> architecturally how to fit energy savings with the existing world.  It
>> can't be considered alone.
>
> Yes, but please: which is your specific concern (if any) regarding
> draft-ietf-6lo-btle?

The concerns:
1. REQUIRE HC is way too much
2. implementation status is not mature enough
3. Bluetooth SIG specs dont talk IPv6

