>> The Bluetooth 4.1 specification and thus BT-LE itself is
>> implemented widely (e.g., in the many current phones, tablets and
>> laptops), so it is important to agree on an IP-over-foo
>> specification for this link layer.

This is not convincing to me.  It is not simply because some link layer
technology is avaialble widely that IP must run on it.

There are many link layers on which IP doesnt run and doesnt need to.
These are typically link layers dedicated to particular applications,
which dont need the power of the IP layer to route through hugely
complex networks.

We must have reasons to make IP run on it.  And these reasons must be
related to the Internet at large, not just local application-specific
connectivity.

If we take these reasons into account then we see more advantages of
connecting BTLE devices to other devices in an end-to-end manner across
wider geographical areas.

