I think you are confusing gateways (in today's parlance) with routers here.
All routers need an adaptation layer to translate IP to the specific MAC
layer packets being used.  This translation may be very simple
encapsulation, as with Ethernet, or something more complicated may be
going on.  All the Internet is not Ethernet.  In 6LoWPAN networks,
encapsulation often involves fragmentation (not needed for BTLE as BTLE
provides its own segmentation and reassembly) and always some form of
header compression.  The latter is a good idea because power usage is
highly dependent on physical layer packet length and because the
combined IPv6 and UDP headers weigh in at 48 bytes, which is often more
than the payloads that we want to transport for IoT applications.

Historically, routers have been called gateways.  That is no longer the
language we use in modern discourse.  We now use the term gateway for
protocol translating entities, which typically need to have some
application layer knowledge (via configuration or dynamic setup) to do
their job.  Gateways are bad because they are complex, they need to be
replaced when application layers change or just a new application needs
to be deployed, and are generally in the way of deploying applications.

No gateways are needed for IPv6 over BTLE.  This enables integrating
Internet applications on BTLE nodes without needing to configure or
setup intermediate gateways.  Very different from your fitbit example.

> I asked packet dumps to understand.  

I agree that having some packet dumps would be very useful.
May I remind people that there is a repository of 6LoWPAN packet dumps at

	http://svn.tools.ietf.org/svn/wg/6lowpan/packets

Getting some pcaps (or any other form of packet dumps) from a live IPv6
over BTLE implementation would be a very useful contribution here.

Maybe we should more systematically bug the authors of the other 6lo
drafts to contribute packet dumps?

GrÃ¼Ãe, Carsten


