Gabriel,

With all due respect.

I think we agreed with Carles on a very short possible text improvement. 
  I will let them decide and I can live with it.

On another hand, I strongly disagree about lack of constructive discussion.

I think BT and BTLE are incompatible technologies and further IPv6 in 
the picture may only make it worse.

Maybe I doubt also about the proposed track: Standards Track.  I would 
rather see this on the EXPERIMENTAL track.

Maybe I doubt about some parts in the shepherd writeup as well.  The 
write up may be misleading in some parts and may mislead decision makers.

For example, the writeup says:
> The low power variant of Bluetooth is commonly specified in revision
> 4.0 of the Bluetooth specifications and commonly referred to as
> Bluetooth 4.0.

This may make think that BTLE is commonly referred to as Bluetooth 4.0. 
  Or, it is not the case.  Bluetooth 4.0 also includes Bluetooth 
classic.  And IPv6 runs ok on Bluetooth classic.  IPv6 runs ok on 
Bluetooth 4.0 w/o this RFC.

Saying what is written above ("commonly referred to"), may make think 
that this RFC (IPv6 over BTLE) is needed in order to make IPv6 over 
Bluetooth 4.0.  Or, that may not be the case.

I guess the writeup can not be changed at this point, but I still think 
it may be misleading to decision making.

> This document describes how IPv6 is transported over
> Bluetooth Low Energy 4.1 using 6LoWPAN techniques.

I think there is no BTLE 4.1.  There is either Bluetooth 4.1, or BTLE 
part of Bluetooth 4.1.

Alex

