>>
>> Le 11/06/2015 15:38, Carsten Bormann a Ã©crit :
>>>>> We are trying to provide the way to connect them to the
>>>>> Internet.
>>>>
>>>> I think you want to "connect" them to the Internet in the same
>>>> way that my fitbit flex dumps its data through a protocol
>>>> gateway.
>>>>
>>>> That is not IP, although you seem keen on making it carry an
>>>> "IP" label.
>>>
>>> Alex,
>>>
>>> I think you are confusing gateways (in today's parlance) with
>>> routers here. All routers need an adaptation layer to translate
>>> IP to the specific MAC layer packets being used.  This
>>> translation may be very simple encapsulation, as with Ethernet,
>>> or something more complicated may be going on.
>>
>> I agree.  But the more these things are complicated the less
>> likely they are to be adopted at an IP layer which must stay
>> simple.
>>
>>> All the Internet is not Ethernet.
>>
>> I agree in a sense.
>>
>> All Internet is not Ethernet _cables_ but 99% of the IPv6 Internet
>> is IPv6/Ethernet RFC2464 and the imitating IPv6-over-foo RFCs.
>>
>> A big chunk of the 1% left is point-to-point links.
>>
>> And then there are of course many IP links which are disconnected
>> from the Internet and which run IP in very different ways than IP
>> on the Internet.  They will never be connected to the Internet.
>>
>>> In 6LoWPAN networks, encapsulation often involves fragmentation
>>> (not needed for BTLE as BTLE provides its own segmentation and
>>> reassembly) and always some form of header compression.  The
>>> latter is a good idea because power usage is highly dependent on
>>> physical layer packet length and because the combined IPv6 and
>>> UDP headers weigh in at 48 bytes, which is often more than the
>>> payloads that we want to transport for IoT applications.
>>
>> This mixes in high-level concepts which are disjoint.
>>
>> For one, these links will be happier if IP is not on them, because
>> IP consumes a lot.
>>
>> Most marketed IoT applications are actually simply two segments: a
>> non-IP link plus an IP link from the bigger computer to a server.
>>
>> The plethora of IoT devices arriving on market dont run IP and dont
>> need IP.  The cellular network operators dont allow for this "IPv6
>> through a smartphone" either.
>>
>> Certainly there can be hypothetical applications which may need to
>> have IP in the end node, direct Thing-to-Thing communications,
>> secure e2e, server in the Thing, and more.  But HC and 6lowpan are
>> not enabling that either, simply because they are not any more
>> "end-to-end" than the deployed Things using nonIP-plus-IP segments.
>> HC and 6lowpan actually continue this tendency of two linked
>> incompatible segments, which break end-to-end.
>>
>>> Historically, routers have been called gateways.  That is no
>>> longer the language we use in modern discourse.
>>>
>>> We now use the term gateway for protocol translating entities,
>>> which typically need to have some application layer knowledge
>>> (via configuration or dynamic setup) to do their job.  Gateways
>>> are bad because they are complex, they need to be replaced when
>>> application layers change or just a new application needs to be
>>> deployed, and are generally in the way of deploying
>>> applications.
>>>
>>> No gateways are needed for IPv6 over BTLE.
>>
>> If no gateways are between me and an IPv6/BTLE device why can't I
>> ping6 one?
>>
>>> This enables integrating Internet applications on BTLE nodes
>>> without needing to configure or setup intermediate gateways.
>>
>> That is a good goal, but I think it is only on paper, sorry if I
>> sound provoking.
>>
>>> Very different from your fitbit example.
>>
>> I agree if it were so.
>>
>>>> I asked packet dumps to understand.
>>>
>>> I agree that having some packet dumps would be very useful. May
>>> I remind people that there is a repository of 6LoWPAN packet
>>> dumps at
>>>
>>> http://svn.tools.ietf.org/svn/wg/6lowpan/packets
>>
>> I checked them all.  All are running on Ethernet II.
>>
>> Would IPv6/BTLE packets also be on Ethernet II?  Would they also
>> exhibit an 6lowpan intermediary header?  (because IPv6/BT doesnt).
>>
>> I still look for packet dumps IPv6/BTLE.
>>
>>> Getting some pcaps (or any other form of packet dumps) from a
>>> live IPv6 over BTLE implementation would be a very useful
>>> contribution here.
>>>
>>> Maybe we should more systematically bug the authors of the other
>>> 6lo drafts to contribute packet dumps?
>>
>> Bugging them - not necessarily, but talk to them about it.  If
>> they provide one here then many people will see it - companies,
>> universities, stds participants.
>>
>> Alex
