Hi Carsten,

Would it be possible to upload the attached packet dumps
(IPv6/Bluetooth2.0 and IPv6/Bluetooth4.0 wireshark and hcidump LCAP
captures) on

http://svn.tools.ietf.org/svn/wg/6lowpan/packets/

I can provide them in other formats if necessary.

For information, on the Internet one can find BTLE wireshark dissectors
and BTLE wireshark packet dumps, although they dont seem to feature IP.

Thanks in advance,

Alex

Le 11/06/2015 15:38, Carsten Bormann a Ã©crit :
>>> We are trying to provide the way to connect them to the
>>> Internet.
>>
>> I think you want to "connect" them to the Internet in the same way
>> that my fitbit flex dumps its data through a protocol gateway.
>>
>> That is not IP, although you seem keen on making it carry an "IP"
>> label.
>
> Alex,
>
> I think you are confusing gateways (in today's parlance) with routers
> here. All routers need an adaptation layer to translate IP to the
> specific MAC layer packets being used.  This translation may be very
> simple encapsulation, as with Ethernet, or something more complicated
> may be going on.  All the Internet is not Ethernet.  In 6LoWPAN
> networks, encapsulation often involves fragmentation (not needed for
> BTLE as BTLE provides its own segmentation and reassembly) and always
> some form of header compression.  The latter is a good idea because
> power usage is highly dependent on physical layer packet length and
> because the combined IPv6 and UDP headers weigh in at 48 bytes, which
> is often more than the payloads that we want to transport for IoT
> applications.
>
> Historically, routers have been called gateways.  That is no longer
> the language we use in modern discourse.  We now use the term gateway
> for protocol translating entities, which typically need to have some
> application layer knowledge (via configuration or dynamic setup) to
> do their job.  Gateways are bad because they are complex, they need
> to be replaced when application layers change or just a new
> application needs to be deployed, and are generally in the way of
> deploying applications.
>
> No gateways are needed for IPv6 over BTLE.  This enables integrating
> Internet applications on BTLE nodes without needing to configure or
> setup intermediate gateways.  Very different from your fitbit
> example.
>
>> I asked packet dumps to understand.
>
> I agree that having some packet dumps would be very useful. May I
> remind people that there is a repository of 6LoWPAN packet dumps at
>
> http://svn.tools.ietf.org/svn/wg/6lowpan/packets
>
> Getting some pcaps (or any other form of packet dumps) from a live
> IPv6 over BTLE implementation would be a very useful contribution
> here.
>
> Maybe we should more systematically bug the authors of the other 6lo
> drafts to contribute packet dumps?
>
> GrÃ¼Ãe, Carsten
