Everyone=E2=80=94

This is my review of I-D.ietf-6lo-6lobac-01.

=E2=80=94 Section 1, page 1 [editorial] Recommend rewriting the last =
sentence of the first paragraph as follows: =E2=80=9CThe general =
approach is to adapt elements of the 6LoWPAN specifications [RFC 4944, =
RFC 6282 and RFC 6775] to constrained wired networks.=E2=80=9D

=E2=80=94 Section 1, page 2 [technical] Recommend appending after the =
final paragraph in the section: =E2=80=9CThis document specifies that =
MS/TP devices with global scope addresses are REQUIRED to use IPv6 =
Neighbor Discovery Compression [RFC 6775] to register opaque 64-bit IIDs =
with their local routers."

=E2=80=94 Section 3, page 5 [editorial] How does this specification =
assume that =E2=80=9Ca unique IPv6 subnet prefix is assigned to each =
MS/TP segment?=E2=80=9D Assuming this means =E2=80=9Cother than the =
link-local prefix fe80::/10.=E2=80=9D I don=E2=80=99t see where this =
assumption is correct. It looks to me like it will work fine if =
fe80::/10 is the only subnet assigned to the link. Indeed the use of the =
MAY keyword in paragraph about global scope addresses in section 6 seems =
to support my observation. Recommend removing the relevant sentence =
noting this assumption.

=E2=80=94 Section 3, page 6 [technical] As Peter van der Stok notes, =
IPv6 multicast should not be REQUIRED to use link-layer broadcast. It =
should suffice to relax that to RECOMMENDED or OPTIONAL.

=E2=80=94 Section 5, page 6 [editorial] RFC 6282 does not =
=E2=80=9Cdeprecate=E2=80=9D the LOWPAN_HC1. It merely provides =
LOWPAN_IPHC as a more widely applicable alternative. Recommend rewriting =
these sentences as follows: =E2=80=9CLoBAC is a subset of the LoWPAN =
encapsulation defined in RFC 4944 and extended in RFC 6282, therefore =
the use of =E2=80=9CLOWPAN=E2=80=9D in the literals below is =
intentional. The principle difference between LoBAC and LoWPAN are the =
omission of the Fragmentation, Mesh, Broadcast and LOWPAN_HC1 headers.

=E2=80=94 Section 5, page 6 [editorial] RFC 6282 redefines the Escape =
header, reserving a new dispatch code for its eventual replacement, and =
this has been the subject of some debate in 6LO recently. In light of =
this, the language in this draft about =E2=80=9Call protocol datagrams =
(=E2=80=A6) SHALL be preceded by one of the valid LoBAC encapsulation =
headers=E2=80=9D should be clarified. Is the dispatch value reserved for =
the Escape replacement, which might be used for RPL artifacts in =
forthcoming documents, a valid LoBAC encapsulation header? (See further =
remarks below.)

=E2=80=94 Section 5, page 6 [technical] =E2=80=9CSHALL=E2=80=9D is not a =
RFC 2119 keyword. Recommend replacing with MUST.

=E2=80=94 Section 5, page 7 [technical] The pattern =E2=80=9C01 =
000000=E2=80=9D used for the ESC code should be described as =E2=80=9Crese=
rved by RFC 6282 for defining a mechanism to allow for more than 64 =
dispatch values,=E2=80=9D c.f. recent discussion on the 6LO working =
group list regarding the erratum reported here: =
<http://www.rfc-editor.org/errata_search.php?rfc=3D4944&eid=3D4359>. As =
an aside, inclusion of the ESC code in the set of valid Dispatch values =
above along with the previously stated requirement that all protocol =
datagrams MUST be preceded by one of the valid LoBAC encapsulation =
headers opens the question of whether the ESC header is an encapsulation =
header. Are protocol datagrams allowed to be encapsulated below whatever =
the ESC header is defined to carry in the future, e.g. the RPL =
artifacts? I don=E2=80=99t think this draft should try to imply =
otherwise, but it might help to call out what the ESC header is actually =
doing in LoBAC. I=E2=80=99m not sure I know, so I leave it to the =
authors to explain.

=E2=80=94 Section 6, page 9 [editorial] the phrases =E2=80=9CIPv6 =
Interface Identifier,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CInterface Identifier=E2=80=9D =
and =E2=80=9CIID" in the first four paragraphs of section 6 should be =
replaced with =E2=80=9CLink-local IPv6 Interface Identifier (IID)=E2=80=9D=
 in the first instance and =E2=80=9CLink-local IID=E2=80=9D in all =
subsequent instances, so as to make clear that these identifiers are not =
to be used with global scope addresses.

=E2=80=94 Section 7, page 9 [editorial] should read =E2=80=9C...formed =
by appending the Link-local IID, as defined above=E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D

=E2=80=94 Section 13, the acknowledgement should include the authors of =
RFC 6282 and RFC 6775 as well.

=E2=80=94james=


