James,

Thanks for taking the time to review this proposal.  Comments inline...

On Wed, Jun 17, 2015 at 6:47 PM, james woodyatt <jhw@nestlabs.com> wrote:

> Everyone=E2=80=94
>
> This is my review of I-D.ietf-6lo-6lobac-01.
>
> =E2=80=94 Section 1, page 1 [editorial] Recommend rewriting the last sent=
ence of
> the first paragraph as follows: =E2=80=9CThe general approach is to adapt=
 elements
> of the 6LoWPAN specifications [RFC 4944, RFC 6282 and RFC 6775] to
> constrained wired networks.=E2=80=9D
>
> OK.


> =E2=80=94 Section 1, page 2 [technical] Recommend appending after the fin=
al
> paragraph in the section: =E2=80=9CThis document specifies that MS/TP dev=
ices with
> global scope addresses are REQUIRED to use IPv6 Neighbor Discovery
> Compression [RFC 6775] to register opaque 64-bit IIDs with their local
> routers."
>
> Sorry, are you talking about ARO?  I'm not sure it's appropriate to
REQUIRE any particular
policy at this layer, particularly if you're thinking along the lines of
ideas proposed in draft-
thaler-6lo-privacy-addrs.


> =E2=80=94 Section 3, page 5 [editorial] How does this specification assum=
e that =E2=80=9Ca
> unique IPv6 subnet prefix is assigned to each MS/TP segment?=E2=80=9D Ass=
uming this
> means =E2=80=9Cother than the link-local prefix fe80::/10.=E2=80=9D I don=
=E2=80=99t see where this
> assumption is correct. It looks to me like it will work fine if fe80::/10
> is the only subnet assigned to the link. Indeed the use of the MAY keywor=
d
> in paragraph about global scope addresses in section 6 seems to support m=
y
> observation. Recommend removing the relevant sentence noting this
> assumption.
>

Good catch.  What I mean is one link-local prefix, and (optionally) one ULA
prefix and/or one Global prefix.

>
> =E2=80=94 Section 3, page 6 [technical] As Peter van der Stok notes, IPv6
> multicast should not be REQUIRED to use link-layer broadcast. It should
> suffice to relax that to RECOMMENDED or OPTIONAL.
>
> See reply to Peter.  Will relax to allow unicast of IPv6 multicast
messages (though that sounds
pretty inefficient).  What is out-of-bounds is re-defining the MS/TP
addressing architecture.

=E2=80=94 Section 5, page 6 [editorial] RFC 6282 does not =E2=80=9Cdeprecat=
e=E2=80=9D the
> LOWPAN_HC1. It merely provides LOWPAN_IPHC as a more widely applicable
> alternative.


See RFC 6282, section 2, para 1.  That seems pretty clearly worded to me.

Recommend rewriting these sentences as follows: =E2=80=9CLoBAC is a subset =
of the
> LoWPAN encapsulation defined in RFC 4944 and extended in RFC 6282,
> therefore the use of =E2=80=9CLOWPAN=E2=80=9D in the literals below is in=
tentional. The
> principle difference between LoBAC and LoWPAN are the omission of the
> Fragmentation, Mesh, Broadcast and LOWPAN_HC1 headers.
>
> I will go back and review this again, but I don't see a need to support
HC1 compression.


> =E2=80=94 Section 5, page 6 [editorial] RFC 6282 redefines the Escape hea=
der,
> reserving a new dispatch code for its eventual replacement, and this has
> been the subject of some debate in 6LO recently. In light of this, the
> language in this draft about =E2=80=9Call protocol datagrams (=E2=80=A6) =
SHALL be preceded
> by one of the valid LoBAC encapsulation headers=E2=80=9D should be clarif=
ied. Is
> the dispatch value reserved for the Escape replacement, which might be us=
ed
> for RPL artifacts in forthcoming documents, a valid LoBAC encapsulation
> header? (See further remarks below.)
>
> I've had enough feedback in support of IPHC that I plan to mandate that
and replace the
whole table with a single codepoint (as in RFC 7428).


> =E2=80=94 Section 5, page 6 [technical] =E2=80=9CSHALL=E2=80=9D is not a =
RFC 2119 keyword.
> Recommend replacing with MUST.
>
> It is in my copy of RFC 2119.  I have no aversion to MUST, but most of th=
e
language in
this section is cribbed from RFC 4944.


> =E2=80=94 Section 5, page 7 [technical] The pattern =E2=80=9C01 000000=E2=
=80=9D used for the ESC
> code should be described as =E2=80=9Creserved by RFC 6282 for defining a =
mechanism
> to allow for more than 64 dispatch values,=E2=80=9D c.f. recent discussio=
n on the
> 6LO working group list regarding the erratum reported here: <
> http://www.rfc-editor.org/errata_search.php?rfc=3D4944&eid=3D4359>. As an
> aside, inclusion of the ESC code in the set of valid Dispatch values abov=
e
> along with the previously stated requirement that all protocol datagrams
> MUST be preceded by one of the valid LoBAC encapsulation headers opens th=
e
> question of whether the ESC header is an encapsulation header. Are protoc=
ol
> datagrams allowed to be encapsulated below whatever the ESC header is
> defined to carry in the future, e.g. the RPL artifacts? I don=E2=80=99t t=
hink this
> draft should try to imply otherwise, but it might help to call out what t=
he
> ESC header is actually doing in LoBAC. I=E2=80=99m not sure I know, so I =
leave it
> to the authors to explain.
>
> As I said above, I'm avoiding it entirely.


> =E2=80=94 Section 6, page 9 [editorial] the phrases =E2=80=9CIPv6 Interfa=
ce Identifier,=E2=80=9D
> =E2=80=9CInterface Identifier=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CIID" in the first fou=
r paragraphs of section 6
> should be replaced with =E2=80=9CLink-local IPv6 Interface Identifier (II=
D)=E2=80=9D in the
> first instance and =E2=80=9CLink-local IID=E2=80=9D in all subsequent ins=
tances, so as to
> make clear that these identifiers are not to be used with global scope
> addresses.
>
> Yes, I need to re-work this.  As an example, RFC 7428 does a good job of
making this distinction.
They use the term "link-layer-derived IPv6 address".


> =E2=80=94 Section 7, page 9 [editorial] should read =E2=80=9C...formed by=
 appending the
> Link-local IID, as defined above=E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D
>

Ibid.


> =E2=80=94 Section 13, the acknowledgement should include the authors of R=
FC 6282
> and RFC 6775 as well.
>
> OK.

Kerry


