>
>> Alexandru Petrescu wrote:
>>
>>> Hello participants to 6lo,
>>>
>>> What is the EtherType for carrying LOWPAN_IPHC headers in Ethernet
>>> frames?
>>>
>>
>> 802.15.4 does not have Ethertypes.
>>
>
> I did not know that?
>
> But in the captures I see the EthernetII header carrying an 802.15.4 Data
> header does have a Type.  I am asking about that type.  What should be it=
s
> value?
>
> The packet I am talking about looks like this:
> EthernetII
> IEEE 802.15.4 Data
> 6LoWPAN
> IPv6 Base Header
> ICMPv6
>
> it's on the website you referred to earlier.


<RCC>As Carsten said, the 802.15.4 network adapters use a variety of means
to wrap packets. In some cases, the wrapping of the 802.15.4 frame is done
directly using an EthernetII frame as you show above. In this case, there
is a field in the Wireshark 802.15.4 preferences called "802.15.4 Ethertype
(in hex)", which can be set appropriately and (I think) is 0x809a by
default. There are other ways of wrapping the frame, including something
called "ZEP". In all cases, you can ignore these outer wrappers (I presume
this is what Carsten meant by "not taking them seriously"); the ZEP wrapper
contains some additional info like channel and LQI</RCC>

>
>  6LoWPAN uses the first byte of the MAC payload (the "dispatch" byte) to
>> indicate the type of frame.  See Figure 2 of RFC 4944.
>>
>
> Ok, noted.  But that is not shown in the packet capture: there is no
> Dispatch byte in these captures.  I guess the spec is right but there are
> no packet captures available?


<RCC>It should be. If you dissect the 6LoWPAN part of the packet you should
see it as the first byte.</RCC>

>
>
>  The 802.15.4 wireshark capture in "dao_with_targetdesc.pcap" (an ICMPv6
>>> packet) features "0x809a"  in the Type field of the EthernetII header.
>>> But I cant seem to find 0x809a in the list of EtherTypes - 0x809a seems
>>> unassigned?  Maybe the capture is wrong?
>>>
>>
>> The pcaps we have were captured using a variety of methods.  These often
>> left somewhat intesting chains of headers around the 6LoWPAN data.
>> Don't take those too seriously.
>>
>
> I need captures that I can take seriously.  And I can provide captures
> that one can take seriously.
>

<RCC>See my earlier comment.</RCC>

>
> I think what we do here should be done seriously, I suppose, or at least
> so I think?
>
>  The capture "wireshark-rpl-prefix.pcap" says "0x0800" which is IPv4,
>>> fine.  But I look for IPv6.
>>>
>>
>> Ditto.
>>
>> We probably should be adding some descriptive text to those samples.
>>
>
> There is a readme file in there... I am already happy such place exists,
> we can understand better, although it can be improved.
>

<RCC>
That may be using the ZEP encapsulation protocol, which wraps like:

EthernetII(EtherType 0x8000)[IPv4[UDP[ZEP[802.15.4]]]]
</RCC>


