Alexandru Petrescu <alexandru.petrescu@gmail.com> wrote:
    > I am not sure whether tcpdump's linktype means the same thing as
    > 'ethertype'?
    > (I never heard of 'linktype'?).

No, it's a value for a file format to indicate what kind of thing
is inside.  It says what kind of layer-2 was captured.
Ethernet is one of the options, in which case ethertype has further meaning
to indicate the layer-3-ish thing.  15.4 is another format, completely
seperate from ethertype.

    > Le 23/06/2015 19:50, Michael Richardson a =C3=A9crit :
    >>
    >> So, the PCAP file format has a type for 802.15.4:
    >> LINKTYPE_IEEE802_15_4
    >>
    >> see: http://www.tcpdump.org/linktypes.html

    > What is the value of LINKTYPE_IEEE802_15_4?  Is it 0x809a?

No, and that's not the point.

The point is that there are other ways to present 802.15.4 packets
in captures.

The use of 0x809a in a fake ethernet layer is just the choice of *one*
wireshark 802.15.4 capture interface, and it is done as a private
interface between two private components.

