>
> Alexandru Petrescu <alexandru.petrescu@gmail.com> wrote:
>> I am not sure whether tcpdump's linktype means the same thing as
>> 'ethertype'? (I never heard of 'linktype'?).
>
> No, it's a value for a file format to indicate what kind of thing is
> inside.  It says what kind of layer-2 was captured. Ethernet is one
> of the options, in which case ethertype has further meaning to
> indicate the layer-3-ish thing.  15.4 is another format, completely
> seperate from ethertype.

Ok, that is file formats, not packet formats.  I agree with you about
file formats and software writers are free to define linktypes.

>> Le 23/06/2015 19:50, Michael Richardson a Ã©crit :
>>>
>>> So, the PCAP file format has a type for 802.15.4:
>>> LINKTYPE_IEEE802_15_4
>>>
>>> see: http://www.tcpdump.org/linktypes.html
>
>> What is the value of LINKTYPE_IEEE802_15_4?  Is it 0x809a?
>
> No, and that's not the point.
>
> The point is that there are other ways to present 802.15.4 packets in
> captures.
>
> The use of 0x809a in a fake ethernet layer is just the choice of
> *one* wireshark 802.15.4 capture interface, and it is done as a
> private interface between two private components.

I agree in that case.

My point is about packet headers carrying 6lowpan headers.  It's these
packet headers which should have an EtherType, if they are in the IEEE
class.

But hold on a second - do you agree there is on the wire a header below
a 6lowpan header?  Or are all the headers that we see in these captures
below 6lowpan just fake?

Alex

