I think we need to clarify things further. Let's take a packet trace from
Wireshark using the Ubisys 802.15.4 Wireshark dongle. The example captured
packet is a CoAP packet going over a 6LoWPAN mesh network. This is the list
of framing, outermost first:

1) Frame 27: 126 bytes on wire (1008 bits), 126 bytes captured (1008 bits)
on interface 0
2) Ethernet II, Src: UbisysTe_00:01:63 (00:1f:ee:00:01:63), Dst: Broadcast
(ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:ff)
3) Internet Protocol Version 4, Src: 0.0.0.0 (0.0.0.0), Dst:
255.255.255.255 (255.255.255.255)
4) User Datagram Protocol, Src Port: 17754 (17754), Dst Port: 17754 (17754)
5) ZigBee Encapsulation Protocol, Channel: 18, Length: 52
6) IEEE 802.15.4 Data, Dst: 0x0000, Src: 0x0400
7) 6LoWPAN
8) Internet Protocol Version 6, Src: fd00:db8::ff:fe00:400
(fd00:db8::ff:fe00:400), Dst: fd00:db8::ff:fe00:0 (fd00:db8::ff:fe00:0)
9) User Datagram Protocol, Src Port: 19789 (19789), Dst Port: 19789 (19789)
10) Constrained Application Protocol, Confirmable, MID:101, POST

So, to be clear, [10] is encapsulated in [9], [9] in [8] and so on. With
6LoWPAN fragmentation, this can look different but in this case it all fits
into one 802.15.4 data frame.

As we all know, encapsulation/layering can be represented as follows:

[Outer Header, Outer Payload[Inner Header, Inner Payload, Inner Footer],
Outer Footer]

So the above can be summarised more or less like the following (I have
assumed no footers to try to simplify the illustration)

[1H,1P:[2H,2P:[3H,3P:[4H,4P:[5H,5P:[6H,6P:[7H,7P:[8H,8P:[9H,9P:[10H,10P[CoA=
P
payload]]]]]]]]]]]

Note this is not exactly correct as will be made clearer later but is a
good enough illustration at this stage. Crucially, in the above *only 6 to
10 is on the ether*, i.e.:

6) IEEE 802.15.4 Data, Dst: 0x0000, Src: 0x0400
7) 6LoWPAN
8) Internet Protocol Version 6, Src: fd00:db8::ff:fe00:400
(fd00:db8::ff:fe00:400), Dst: fd00:db8::ff:fe00:0 (fd00:db8::ff:fe00:0)
9) User Datagram Protocol, Src Port: 19789 (19789), Dst Port: 19789 (19789)
10) Constrained Application Protocol, Confirmable, MID:101, POST

All the other encapsulating frames are added by the network adapter:

1) Frame 27: 126 bytes on wire (1008 bits), 126 bytes captured (1008 bits)
on interface 0
2) Ethernet II, Src: UbisysTe_00:01:63 (00:1f:ee:00:01:63), Dst: Broadcast
(ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:ff)
3) Internet Protocol Version 4, Src: 0.0.0.0 (0.0.0.0), Dst:
255.255.255.255 (255.255.255.255)
4) User Datagram Protocol, Src Port: 17754 (17754), Dst Port: 17754 (17754)
5) ZigBee Encapsulation Protocol, Channel: 18, Length: 52

As Carsten pointed out, we don't really care about (1) to (5). So lets take
framing (6) to (10) on the ether one by one:

6) IEEE 802.15.4 Data, Dst: 0x0000, Src: 0x0400

This is the 802.15.4 MAC data frame and these are the bytes you will see on
the ether. The MAC header shows it going from 0x0400 to 0x0000 layer 2
addresses. The payload (aka MAC SDU) is the 6LoWPAN frame. There is also a
MAC footer in this case; the 16-bit CRC.

7) 6LoWPAN

This is the 6LoWPAN IPHC header followed by the data which in total
comprises the compressed version of the IPv6 packet

8) Internet Protocol Version 6, Src: fd00:db8::ff:fe00:400
(fd00:db8::ff:fe00:400), Dst: fd00:db8::ff:fe00:0 (fd00:db8::ff:fe00:0)

This is the only place where Wireshark deviates somewhat, as (8) is the
uncompressed IPv6 representation of (7), where the IPHC compressed fields
have been expanded into the full IPv6 header. This means (8) is not
actually the payload of (7).

9) User Datagram Protocol, Src Port: 19789 (19789), Dst Port: 19789 (19789)

The UDP datagram is the payload of the IPv6 packet

10) Constrained Application Protocol, Confirmable, MID:101, POST

The CoAP message is the payload of the UDP datagram.

I hope this makes it clearer what is one the ether and what isn't. With
regard to the original point, the EthernetII frame (2) is *not* on the
ether.

Robert

