Robert,

Thank you very much.  I find it very valuable overall.

I have however a few comments.

Le 24/06/2015 20:09, Robert Cragie a Ã©crit :
> I think we need to clarify things further. Let's take a packet trace
> from Wireshark using the Ubisys 802.15.4 Wireshark dongle. The example
> captured packet is a CoAP packet going over a 6LoWPAN mesh network. This
> is the list of framing, outermost first:
>
> 1) Frame 27: 126 bytes on wire (1008 bits), 126 bytes captured (1008
> bits) on interface 0
> 2) Ethernet II, Src: UbisysTe_00:01:63 (00:1f:ee:00:01:63), Dst:
> Broadcast (ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:ff)
> 3) Internet Protocol Version 4, Src: 0.0.0.0 (0.0.0.0), Dst:
> 255.255.255.255 (255.255.255.255)
> 4) User Datagram Protocol, Src Port: 17754 (17754), Dst Port: 17754 (17754)
> 5) ZigBee Encapsulation Protocol, Channel: 18, Length: 52
> 6) IEEE 802.15.4 Data, Dst: 0x0000, Src: 0x0400
> 7) 6LoWPAN
> 8) Internet Protocol Version 6, Src: fd00:db8::ff:fe00:400
> (fd00:db8::ff:fe00:400), Dst: fd00:db8::ff:fe00:0 (fd00:db8::ff:fe00:0)
> 9) User Datagram Protocol, Src Port: 19789 (19789), Dst Port: 19789 (19789)
> 10) Constrained Application Protocol, Confirmable, MID:101, POST

I see the headers in the same manner. Some emulators of other protocols
act that way as well, encapsulating everything in IPv4. But yes, that
encapsulation is local just to have a transport for testing the main
protocol.

> So, to be clear, [10] is encapsulated in [9], [9] in [8] and so on. With
> 6LoWPAN fragmentation, this can look different but in this case it all
> fits into one 802.15.4 data frame.
>
> As we all know, encapsulation/layering can be represented as follows:
>
> [Outer Header, Outer Payload[Inner Header, Inner Payload, Inner Footer],
> Outer Footer]
>
> So the above can be summarised more or less like the following (I have
> assumed no footers to try to simplify the illustration)

Yes, it is good to assume no footers in some cases because some carriers
dont put footers (IPv6 has no footers/trailers, although IPv6 ESP tunnel
mode does feature such).

> [1H,1P:[2H,2P:[3H,3P:[4H,4P:[5H,5P:[6H,6P:[7H,7P:[8H,8P:[9H,9P:[10H,10P[CoAP
> payload]]]]]]]]]]]
>
> Note this is not exactly correct as will be made clearer later but is a
> good enough illustration at this stage. Crucially, in the above *only 6
> to 10 is on the ether*, i.e.:
>
> 6) IEEE 802.15.4 Data, Dst: 0x0000, Src: 0x0400
> 7) 6LoWPAN
> 8) Internet Protocol Version 6, Src: fd00:db8::ff:fe00:400
> (fd00:db8::ff:fe00:400), Dst: fd00:db8::ff:fe00:0 (fd00:db8::ff:fe00:0)
> 9) User Datagram Protocol, Src Port: 19789 (19789), Dst Port: 19789 (19789)
> 10) Constrained Application Protocol, Confirmable, MID:101, POST

Ok, so the 15.4 header is on the wire. I tend to agree with you.

> All the other encapsulating frames are added by the network adapter:
>
> 1) Frame 27: 126 bytes on wire (1008 bits), 126 bytes captured (1008
> bits) on interface 0
> 2) Ethernet II, Src: UbisysTe_00:01:63 (00:1f:ee:00:01:63), Dst:
> Broadcast (ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:ff)
> 3) Internet Protocol Version 4, Src: 0.0.0.0 (0.0.0.0), Dst:
> 255.255.255.255 (255.255.255.255)
> 4) User Datagram Protocol, Src Port: 17754 (17754), Dst Port: 17754 (17754)
> 5) ZigBee Encapsulation Protocol, Channel: 18, Length: 52
>
> As Carsten pointed out, we don't really care about (1) to (5). So lets
> take framing (6) to (10) on the ether one by one:
>
> 6) IEEE 802.15.4 Data, Dst: 0x0000, Src: 0x0400
>
> This is the 802.15.4 MAC data frame and these are the bytes you will see
> on the ether. The MAC header shows it going from 0x0400 to 0x0000 layer
> 2 addresses. The payload (aka MAC SDU) is the 6LoWPAN frame. There is
> also a MAC footer in this case; the 16-bit CRC.

YEs, and deployers of IPv6-over-15.4 must be able to use MAC src and dst
addresses other than 0x0. That 0x0 is wrong.

The MAC src and dst addresses have very strong relationship with the
link-local and multicast IPv6 addresses (e.g. MAC address 33::1
corresponds to ff02::1, and vice-versa). One can't have ff02::1 in the
IP dst address field and 0 in the MAC dst field, it's incompatible.

I suggest we at least try to come up with MAC addresses to use in the
15.4 header.

>
> 7) 6LoWPAN
>
> This is the 6LoWPAN IPHC header followed by the data which in total
> comprises the compressed version of the IPv6 packet
>
> 8) Internet Protocol Version 6, Src: fd00:db8::ff:fe00:400
> (fd00:db8::ff:fe00:400), Dst: fd00:db8::ff:fe00:0 (fd00:db8::ff:fe00:0)
>
> This is the only place where Wireshark deviates somewhat, as (8) is the
> uncompressed IPv6 representation of (7), where the IPHC compressed
> fields have been expanded into the full IPv6 header. This means (8) is
> not actually the payload of (7).

This deviation is because the programmer does not know how to do. So she
hacks something.

> 9) User Datagram Protocol, Src Port: 19789 (19789), Dst Port: 19789 (19789)
>
> The UDP datagram is the payload of the IPv6 packet
>
> 10) Constrained Application Protocol, Confirmable, MID:101, POST
>
> The CoAP message is the payload of the UDP datagram.
>
> I hope this makes it clearer what is one the ether and what isn't.

YEs it does, thanks for the clarification.

I suggest to insert an additional LLC header between the 15.4 header and
the 6lowpan header. And that header to carry an EtherType. That
EtherType could be requested new for 6lowpan, as an option. So people
who want to use 6lowpan compressed headers will be able to use it. They
will gain in reducing header sizes.

I also suggest if someone does not want to use 6lowpan compressed
headers - use that same LLC header but with EtherType 0x86dd (IPv6 Base
Header). They will gain in end-to-end connectivity to the IPv6 Internet,
end-to-end IPsec, etc.

What do you think?

IMHO there are some advantages in putting an LLC over 15.4 in terms of
compatibility, bridging, link-layer security. This (setting an LLC over
15.4) would be some work to do at IEEE, not at IETF, but
that's a matter of interfacing. At IETF we could formulate requirements.

Another advantage of that LLC is that it would work over the 802.11ah
headers as well (there's an IPv6/802.11ah draft in this group) and over
Bluetooth as well.

> With regard to the original point, the EthernetII frame (2) is *not*
> on the ether.

I agree. That EthernetII is in some implementation (here) to make it
easier for the IPv6 stack. It is not on the ether.

If we add an LLC header over the 15.4 header then a widely-implemented
Adaptation Layer will transform the 15.4 header and the LLC header into
an EthernetII header, locally, to make it easier for the IPv6 stack
wireshark programmers.

Alex

