Uh?

Some doc says that a 0x0 16-bit MAC address is valid?  Because a 48bit 
MAC address 0x0 can only be used by Xerox whereas the hardware of this 
dump seems to be Ubisys.

Anyways, my point is that there should be a relationship between the MAC 
address and the IP address.  Whereas this relationship is exhibited by 
this particular packet is maybe not important.  But the relationship 
should be there.

If one sends an RA on a 15.4 link then the dst MAC address of that RA 
must be a MAC multicast address, in relationship with the IPv6 multicast 
address.  (I think you agree that one can send an RA on a 15.4 link 
without a 6lowpan header?)

>     The MAC src and dst addresses have very strong relationship with the
>     link-local and multicast IPv6 addresses (e.g. MAC address 33::1
>     corresponds to ff02::1, and vice-versa). One can't have ff02::1 in the
>     IP dst address field and 0 in the MAC dst field, it's incompatible.
>
>     I suggest we at least try to come up with MAC addresses to use in the
>     15.4 header.
>
>
