Hi Alex,

Further comments inline, bracketed by <RCC2></RCC2>. I think you should
take some time and use Wireshark to carefully analyse the packets in the
examples you pointed to (http://svn.tools.ietf.org/svn/wg/6lowpan/packets/)
then it should become clearer.

Robert

[snip]
>


> Uh?
>
> Some doc says that a 0x0 16-bit MAC address is valid?


<RCC2>Table 1 in 802.15.4-2011.</RCC2>


> Anyways, my point is that there should be a relationship between the MAC
> address and the IP address.  Whereas this relationship is exhibited by this
> particular packet is maybe not important.  But the relationship should be
> there.
>

<RCC2>The relationship is there. Prefix is fd00:db8::/64 (context ID 0).
IID is based on 16-bit address of 0x0000 according to RFC 6282</RCC2>

>
> If one sends an RA on a 15.4 link then the dst MAC address of that RA must
> be a MAC multicast address, in relationship with the IPv6 multicast
> address.  (I think you agree that one can send an RA on a 15.4 link without
> a 6lowpan header?)


<RCC2>Not if you are using 6LoWPAN. RA is an ICMPv6 packet, therefore has a
6LoWPAN header. I can give you an example from ZigBee IP if you want,
although we tended to use it unicast there as specified in RFC 6775</RCC2>

>
>
>      The MAC src and dst addresses have very strong relationship with the
>>     link-local and multicast IPv6 addresses (e.g. MAC address 33::1
>>     corresponds to ff02::1, and vice-versa). One can't have ff02::1 in the
>>     IP dst address field and 0 in the MAC dst field, it's incompatible.
>>
>>     I suggest we at least try to come up with MAC addresses to use in the
>>     15.4 header.
>>
>>
>> <RCC>I have no idea what you are talking about here. 0x0000 is a unicast
>> MAC address so has nothing to do with ff02::/64, which is a multicast
>> address. It isn't ff02::1 in the destination field anyway, it is
>> fd00:db8::ff:fe00:0 as shown below. In other words, an IPv6 SLAAC
>> address of 0x0000 using a 6LoWPAN context according to RFC6282.</RCC>
>>
>
> Ok, I conflated multicast - sorry, but now SLAAC is conflated into
> discussion.
>
> My point is that there is a relationship between the MAC addresses and the
> IPv6 addresses ("address mapping") which needs to be there.


<RCC2>See earlier comment</RCC2>

[snip]

No, I am not saying that.
>
> Yes - many MAC/PHYs may take advantage of 6lowpan headers.
>
> But also yes - many MAC/PHYs for constrained networks can run IPv6 without
> 6lowpan headers.


<RCC2>I thought you were talking about a potential Ethertype for 6LoWPAN so
am a bit confused now.</RCC2>

[snip]


> <RCC>There used to be a SSCS for an IEEE 802.2 Type 1 LLC in
>> 802.15.4-2006 (Annex A) but this was removed in the latest spec
>> (802.15.4-2011). I am not sure why but the IEEE must have had good
>> reason to remove it.</RCC>
>>
>
> Is SSCS for 802.2 Type 1 LLC the same as the LLC we see for WiFi?
>
> Why there is no LLC for 802.15.4?


<RCC2>I don't know why it was removed - I wasn't participating in IEEE at
the time</RCC2>

[snip]


> Just one detail: that pcap you refer to above does not contain an LLC
> header, and hence no EtherType.  It contains a 6lowpan header between an
> apparently uncompressed (but compressed in reality) IPv6 Base Header and an
> ICMPv6 header.
>

<RCC2>
That's not right. Let's analyse what Wireshark shows:

1) Frame 1: 69 bytes on wire (552 bits), 69 bytes captured (552 bits)
2) Ethernet II, Src: 3a:3b:3c:3d:3e:3f (3a:3b:3c:3d:3e:3f), Dst:
IPv6mcast_3c:3d:3e:3f (33:33:3c:3d:3e:3f)
--------
3) IEEE 802.15.4 Data, Dst: Broadcast, Src: 0x3344
4) 6LoWPAN
5) Internet Protocol Version 6, Src: fe80::ff:fe00:3344
(fe80::ff:fe00:3344), Dst: ff02::1a (ff02::1a)
6) Internet Control Message Protocol v6

Again, to be clear, *(1) and (2) are not in the ether* (hence the
separator).

(1) Frame 1: 69 bytes on wire (552 bits), 69 bytes captured (552 bits)

Simply what Wireshark sees as a frame capture - no need to discuss further

2) Ethernet II, Src: 3a:3b:3c:3d:3e:3f (3a:3b:3c:3d:3e:3f), Dst:
IPv6mcast_3c:3d:3e:3f (33:33:3c:3d:3e:3f)

This is the EthernetII frame added by the network adapter. As discussed at
length, this is used to make it easier to interface to the network adapter.
The MAC addresses are not really relevant, except that the destination is a
multicast, which ties in with the lower 802.15.4 frame. The EtherType (not
shown in the summary) is 0x809a.

3) IEEE 802.15.4 Data, Dst: Broadcast, Src: 0x3344

MAC data frame from 0x3344 to 0xffff (i.e, broadcast) *in the ether*

4) 6LoWPAN

6LoWPAN IPHC header

5) Internet Protocol Version 6, Src: fe80::ff:fe00:3344
(fe80::ff:fe00:3344), Dst: ff02::1a (ff02::1a)

I think this maybe where the confusion is. As explained earlier, (5) is NOT
the payload of (4) but the uncompressed IPv6 representation of (4). It is
equivalent full IPv6 packet which comes from the expansion of the 6LoWPAN
IPHC header.

6) Internet Control Message Protocol v6

RPL control message; a DAO with 3 RPL options (RPL Target, RPL Target
Descriptor and Transit Information)

</RCC2>


>
> What would be needed is an LLC header on top of 15.4, and below an
> uncompressed IPv6 Base Header:
>
> (no EthernetII)
> 802.15.4 Data
> LLC Header
> IPv6 Base Header
> payload
>
> What do you think?
>

<RCC2>
That is not right at all. You still seem to be missing the point that the
EthernetII frame is simply added by the network adapter and is not on the
wire/ether. You also seem to have lost the 6LoWPAN header which is what
adapts IPv6 to 802.15.4.

Please take the time to use Wireshark to carefully analyse the packets in
details to see the structure and where the bytes fit in then it should all
become clear.
</RCC2>

--001a11c34eb4d1516a05195b5677
