>
> Robert
>
>     [snip]
>
>     Uh?
>
>     Some doc says that a 0x0 16-bit MAC address is valid?
>
>
> <RCC2>Table 1 in 802.15.4-2011.</RCC2>
>
>     Anyways, my point is that there should be a relationship between the
>     MAC address and the IP address.  Whereas this relationship is
>     exhibited by this particular packet is maybe not important.  But the
>     relationship should be there.
>
>
> <RCC2>The relationship is there. Prefix is fd00:db8::/64 (context ID 0).
> IID is based on 16-bit address of 0x0000 according to RFC 6282</RCC2>

That is one kind of relationship.  This kind of relationship should be 
optional - one must have an option of deriving, or not deriving, an IPv6 
address from a MAC address.  That is for privacy protection against 
attackers who make associations.

But I meant another kind of relationship - the address mapping.  The 
'address mapping' is described in sections 6 and 7 of RFC2464 (unicast 
and mc).

For example, RFC2464 section 6 gives an encoding format of a 48bit MAC 
address into a Source or Target ll address (these are used in ND).  Or, 
RFC6282 defines 16bit MAC addresses yet it does not give a means to 
encode a 16bit MAC address into a Source or Target ll address.  Why so?

>     If one sends an RA on a 15.4 link then the dst MAC address of that
>     RA must be a MAC multicast address, in relationship with the IPv6
>     multicast address.  (I think you agree that one can send an RA on a
>     15.4 link without a 6lowpan header?)
>
>
> <RCC2>Not if you are using 6LoWPAN. RA is an ICMPv6 packet, therefore
> has a 6LoWPAN header.

No, I disagree with this logic.  An ICMPv6 packet should be - optionally 
- carried by an IPv6 Base Header.  In some 15.4 deployments it may  be 
carried by a 6lowpan header but in other 15.4 deployments it may be 
carried by an IPv6 Base Header.

> I can give you an example from ZigBee IP if you
> want, although we tended to use it unicast there as specified in RFC
> 6775</RCC2>

I dont understand.  Now we bring RFC6775 "ND for 6lowpans" in the 
picture.  If you want my oppinion - that RFC6775 also requires header 
compression and I disagree mandating it.  I think ND can run on 15.4 and 
other low-power links - optionally - without header compression.

That RFC ignores too that a Source/Target LL address is needed - 
optionally - for ND and it does not encode the 16bit MAC addresses.

[...]
>
> [snip]
>
>     No, I am not saying that.
>
>     Yes - many MAC/PHYs may take advantage of 6lowpan headers.
>
>     But also yes - many MAC/PHYs for constrained networks can run IPv6
>     without 6lowpan headers.
>
>
> <RCC2>I thought you were talking about a potential Ethertype for 6LoWPAN
> so am a bit confused now.</RCC2>

YEs - EtherType for LOWPAN_IPHC.  This EtherType should be in a field of 
an LLC header.  This LLC header could sit on top of a 15.4 header or on 
top of a 802.11DataHeader.

How can I clarify?

> [snip]
>
>         <RCC>There used to be a SSCS for an IEEE 802.2 Type 1 LLC in
>         802.15.4-2006 (Annex A) but this was removed in the latest spec
>         (802.15.4-2011). I am not sure why but the IEEE must have had good
>         reason to remove it.</RCC>
>
>
>     Is SSCS for 802.2 Type 1 LLC the same as the LLC we see for WiFi?
>
>     Why there is no LLC for 802.15.4?
>
>
> <RCC2>I don't know why it was removed - I wasn't participating in IEEE
> at the time</RCC2>

How can we find out?

And, do you think that LLC could play the role of an LLC header on top 
of a 15.4 header?

> [snip]
>
>     Just one detail: that pcap you refer to above does not contain an
>     LLC header, and hence no EtherType.  It contains a 6lowpan header
>     between an apparently uncompressed (but compressed in reality) IPv6
>     Base Header and an ICMPv6 header.
>
>
> <RCC2>
> That's not right. Let's analyse what Wireshark shows:
>
> 1) Frame 1: 69 bytes on wire (552 bits), 69 bytes captured (552 bits)
> 2) Ethernet II, Src: 3a:3b:3c:3d:3e:3f (3a:3b:3c:3d:3e:3f), Dst:
> IPv6mcast_3c:3d:3e:3f (33:33:3c:3d:3e:3f)
> --------
> 3) IEEE 802.15.4 Data, Dst: Broadcast, Src: 0x3344
> 4) 6LoWPAN
> 5) Internet Protocol Version 6, Src: fe80::ff:fe00:3344
> (fe80::ff:fe00:3344), Dst: ff02::1a (ff02::1a)
> 6) Internet Control Message Protocol v6
>
> Again, to be clear, *(1) and (2) are not in the ether* (hence the
> separator).

I am saying in the capture above there is no LLC header between 3 and 4. 
  Do you agree?

I am not talking about what is put on the ether or not.  I am talking 
about the absence of an LLC header between 3 (15.4) and 4 (6LoWPAN).

> (1) Frame 1: 69 bytes on wire (552 bits), 69 bytes captured (552 bits)
>
> Simply what Wireshark sees as a frame capture - no need to discuss further
>
> 2) Ethernet II, Src: 3a:3b:3c:3d:3e:3f (3a:3b:3c:3d:3e:3f), Dst:
> IPv6mcast_3c:3d:3e:3f (33:33:3c:3d:3e:3f)
>
> This is the EthernetII frame added by the network adapter. As discussed
> at length, this is used to make it easier to interface to the network
> adapter. The MAC addresses are not really relevant, except that the
> destination is a multicast, which ties in with the lower 802.15.4 frame.
> The EtherType (not shown in the summary) is 0x809a.

Agree with the description but I disagree they use 0x809a.  Even if it 
is not put in the wire, this use creates a local incompatibility between 
processes on the same machine.

It's as if I use 193.23.23.1 on my laptop because I know it is not 
allocated to somebody else even though it is not allocated to me either.

> 3) IEEE 802.15.4 Data, Dst: Broadcast, Src: 0x3344
>
> MAC data frame from 0x3344 to 0xffff (i.e, broadcast) *in the ether*

Here we can discuss.  That 0xffff is agreed by IEEE to be a broadcast 
address?

Is IEEE agreeing that broadcast is the right way to work in constrained 
networks, or should it rather be multicast?

I am asking because earlier IEEE decided that 48bit-MAC broadcast 
addresses 0xffffff were not the right way to work on (at that time) 
constrained devices and came up with 48bit-MAC multicast addresses and 
MAC multicast concepts.

A 16bit-MAC multicast address would look like this: 0x3301 for 
all-nodes, 0x3302 for all-hosts, 0x3303 for all-routers.  Do these 16bit 
multicast addresses exist at IEEE?  If yes, we could propose mappings 
between these and IPv6 multicast addresses.  If no, we could request 
IEEE to make them first and then we do the mappings.

> 4) 6LoWPAN
>
> 6LoWPAN IPHC header
>
> 5) Internet Protocol Version 6, Src: fe80::ff:fe00:3344
> (fe80::ff:fe00:3344), Dst: ff02::1a (ff02::1a)
>
> I think this maybe where the confusion is. As explained earlier, (5) is
> NOT the payload of (4) but the uncompressed IPv6 representation of (4).

I agree.  That 5 is an uncompressed representation of 4.

> It is equivalent full IPv6 packet which comes from the expansion of the
> 6LoWPAN IPHC header.

I agree.

What I mean is when there is no IPHC header, there should be an option 
to run uncompressedIPv6BaseHEader on LLC on 15.4.

> 6) Internet Control Message Protocol v6
>
> RPL control message; a DAO with 3 RPL options (RPL Target, RPL Target
> Descriptor and Transit Information)

Yes, I agree.

> </RCC2>
>
>
>     What would be needed is an LLC header on top of 15.4, and below an
