Hi Robert,

Thank you for reply.

YEs, progress seems slow.  I will not bother with further comments. 
Maybe best is to sit down and write draft.

I agree that 6lowpan header compression is ok.

The rfc4944 dispatch type in absence of 6lowpan - maybe, depending on 
what IEEE LLC may want to do.

IID formation from RFC6282 - I didnt know it.  Yes, I discover it does 
provide a means to form an IID out of the 16bit short MAC address.  No, 
it does not provide a means to map 16bit multicast MAC addresses (they 
dont exist, IEEE must make them) into IPv6 multicast addresses.

Pat Kinney - I will ask him the situation of a speculative LLC for 15.4, 
thanks for the pointer.

Why multicast 15.4 was not in the spec?  Multicast is a well-known means 
to reduce power consumption.

802.3 is not a 802.15.4 - yes.  And neither are 802.11, LTE, USB, 
Bluetooth4.0 to name a few that I know well - yet there are adaptation 
layers for each towards EthernetII headers.  Why is 802.15.4 different?

Dispatch byte 0x41 of Dispatch Type and Header of RFC4944 - I dont find 
it in the dumps of http://svn.tools.ietf.org/svn/wg/6lowpan/packets/

The other thread - let's see.

Yours,

Alex



